surveys.narrative: The present fish population is the result of stocking after the fall 1981 lake rehabilitation, with the exception of the black bullhead and black crappie which were from an unknown source. Bluegills were found at above the local median level, but most (70%) were 6.0" or greater in length, indicating good quality. Walleye and largemouth bass were found at above local median numbers. The channel catfish is the result of the fall 1981 stocking. Hybrid muskies stocked in fall 1983 were not sampled.

A number of undesirable species have been noted to be present in Lake Rebecca at this time. There are records of gizzard shad, black bullhead, black crappie, and hybrid sunfish showing up since the 1981 rehab. One gizzard shad, 3 black bullheads, and 97 black crappies were captured this year. The black crappie catch rate is four times the local median. (Length 4.5-9.0"). Walleye and channel catfish are known to be present but none were sampled. A total of 227 bluegills were captured at a rate of 56.75 fish per set vs. 41.6 in 1986. This number per set is more than double the local median of 20.42. The PSD value has increased to 68.8% from 50.5% in 1986. The greatest number of bluegills captured fell in the 6.0-6.4 inch group. Largemouth bass were sampled by trapnets and electrofishing. Legal size (16" minimum) fish are present. The LMB catch rate is equivalent to the state median and two times the local median.

Northern pike, black bullhead, and walleye were sampled at below local median abundance. Carp, white sucker, and bluegill were found at near median levels. Bluegill PSD was 41.4. Gizzard shad, black crappie, and yellow perch were sampled at above median levels. Largemouth bass were sampled in all gear types, and natural reproduction verified by 1/4" trapnets. Four year-classes of bass showed good growth rates. A hybrid muskie and smallmouth bass were sampled by electrofishing. The hybrid muskie from the 1989 stocking showed good growth. Gizzard shad, smallmouth bass, sauger, yellow perch, and carp were likely introduced to Rebecca Lake by a temporary failure of the fish barrier.

Lake Rebecca, a remnant of an abandoned channel of the adjacent Mississippi river, is entirely encompassed by Lake Rebecca Park, owned by the City of Hastings and the US Army Corps of Engineers. Rebecca Lake is aerated in the winter. Water quality of the lake is poor as a result of nutrient loading from storm sewers, street runoff and influxes from the Mississippi River and nearby agricultural activities. Surface water zoning prohibits all but electric motors on the lake. Facilities in the park include a boat landing, fishing pier and wharf, walking trails along with Porta Potties and a picnic area. Extensive shore fishing areas can also be found at Rebecca Lake. The lake is frequently inundated by flood waters of the Mississippi and the fish population reflects the influence that flooding events can have on adjacent waters.
Bluegill and Crappie species made up most of the catch in 2018. Bluegill were common and relatively abundant for lakes similar to Rebecca. Average size of Bluegill sampled was good, with an average size measuring more than 6 inches in length. Crappie sampled in 2018 were generally small, with all Crappie sampled being smaller than 10 inches. Northern Pike were sampled in above average numbers in 2018, and were of good size, averaging 27 inches. Common Carp were sampled in low numbers in 2018, and ranged from 23.4 to 28.2 inches. Other fish observed in low abundance were seven Bowfin and six Yellow Bullhead. Bowfin had a mean length of 25.1 inches and were of good size while Yellow Bullhead mean length was 12.5 inches.

One 24" northern pike was captured. One hybrid muskellunge was captured that was 33" and IV years old showed considerably fast growth. Three walleyes were caught, 16", 17", and 22" and exhibited good growth. Carp, black bullhead, and green sunfish were below median numbers and black crappies are 8.5 times above and they were mainly of the 6.5" group.

The fish population of Lake Rebecca was eliminated with rotenone in the fall of 1981. Prior to treatment fish found with high populations were: gizzard shad, black crappie and white crappie; populations of average (or expected) dimensions were: bowfin, bigmouth buffalo, carp, freshwater drum, black bullhead, brown bullhead, yellow bullhead, yellow perch, and northern pike; those species with low populations were: bluegill, spotted sucker and white sucker.

Bluegill and crappie made up most of the catch in 2012. Bluegill were common, but not abundant. Average size of bluegill sampled was good, with more than 30 percent of the bluegill sampled measuring more than 7" in length. Crappie sampled in 2012 were generally small, with only one crappie larger than 9" observed. Northern pike were sampled in average numbers in 2012, and were large. The average size northern pike observed was 30" long and weighed 6.5 pounds. Largemouth bass were sampled in average numbers, with some larger fish present in the catch. One bass in 5 sampled exceeded 16" in length. Walleye, sauger and channel catfish were sampled in very low numbers in 2012.

The channel catfish, smallmouth bass, and walleye fry stocked were not sampled in the netting. The bluegill stocked in 1982 were hand sorted by sex and only males stocked. A total of 73 adult bluegill were caught and 71 or 97% were males. Growth was good with 70 of 73 of the stocked fish or 95.8% being 7.0 inches or larger. Some natural reproduction of bluegills was noted. Walleye fingerlings and yearlings stocked in the fall of 1981 were both taken in netting with the largest (yearlings) being 14.0 inches (approximately 1.0 pound). Largemouth bass from 3.0 to 5.4 inches were taken. Also taken were two black bullheads which escaped treatment.

Only 18 bluegill were captured. Eight of which were in the 7.0" group. The bluegill PSD increased from 50.5% in 1988 to 77.8% in 1989. One to five year old largemouth bass were present and showed average growth. A strong largemouth bass YOY class was represented in the seining sample. One five year old hybrid muskellunge was shocked. Two and five year old walleye were sampled by electrofishing. Sauger and smallmouth bass of desirable size were also captured electrofishing. Eleven 17-20" carp were netted. Black bullhead and black crappie numbers were well above the medians and yellow perch were slightly below median levels. Small mesh trapnet catches also showed the presence of gizzard shad and white suckers. It is unknown how these species became introduced into this lake, but it is suspected they were stocked by anglers from the nearby Mississippi River.

Rebecca Lake's largemouth bass population remains stable; with fair numbers of fish, as well as good size fish. Thirty largemouth bass were captured by electrofishing on August 15, 1996. This is up from 1995, but a little below the lake's long term average. These fish ranged from just under eight to twenty-two inches long. Average length was just under thirteen inches. Over half of the fish were greater than twelve inches long and one third were greater than sixteen inches long. The lake's bluegill population remains low, but with good size fish. One angler commented to DNR crew on difficulty in catching bluegill. Three quarter of the bluegill captured during the assessment were greater than six inches long, and just over one quarter were greater than seven inches long. Black crappie were the most abundant fish, but were small - no fish greater than seven and a half inches long and over 90% were between five and a half and seven inches long. Northern pike catch was up from previous assessments. Fish were between twenty-one and thirty-three inches long, with two over thirty inches. Northern pike growth rate is very good. Yellow perch catch was also up, but fish were small - no fish over six and a half inches long, and 75% between five and six inches long. Walleye remain uncommon - only three were captured. These ranged from seventeen to twenty-two inches long. Other fish captured were: one smallmouth bass; two yellow bullhead; one black bullhead; eight common carp; and six white sucker. No tiger muskie were captured.

Bluegill were the most abundant species sampled in the 2001 survey. The trap net catch rate was the highest observed for this lake since 1985. The average bluegill captured was 6.45 inches and 0.19 pounds (5.26 fish/pound). Approximately 30% of all bluegill sampled were 7.0 inches or larger. Black crappie were sampled above median levels for abundance and averaged 7.8 inches and 0.29 pounds (3/4 fish/pound). A few white crappies averaging 10.5 inches were also captured. White bass are also present in good numbers with the average fish captured being 11.5 inches and 0.76 pounds. Northern pike were sampled in good numbers for combined gear types. The average size of northern pike sampled was 25.8 inches and 4.1 pounds. Of all northern pike captured, 20% were 30.0 inches or larger. Largemouth bass were sampled near median levels for abundance. The average largemouth bass collected was 11.3 inches and 0.8 pounds. Smallmouth bass are also present in the lake. Walleye and sauger are present even though neither species has been stocked here since the lake was reclaimed in Fall 1997. The average walleye sampled was 17.8 inches and 1.8 pounds. The average sauger was 13.8 inches and 0.78 pounds. These species migrated into the lake when the Mississippi River reached flood stage in Spring 2001. Channel catfish have been stocked since 1998 and are doing well. The average channel catfish collected was 17.1 inches and 1.8 pounds.

The species of interest in the netting were the bluegills which were above state and local medians in numbers but small in size. Black bullhead, black crappie, and hybrid sunfish were found at below local median levels and are from an unknown source. Walleye and largemouth bass were sampled at near local median levels in trapnets. Hybrid muskies stocked in 1983 were not sampled, but anglers reported catches.

The present fish population of walleye, largemouth bass, and bluegill are the result of stocking after the fall 1981 lake rehabilitation. Bluegills are found at a level above the local median number. Approximately 24% of bluegills sampled were above 6.0" in length, indicating good quality. Largemouth bass appear to be abundant. The black bullhead sampled may have survived the chemical rehabilitation or may be the result of an illegal stocking. A total of 60 muskie/northern pike hybrids were stocked in fall 1983 to provide a trophy fishery.

Trapnetting indices showed black bullhead and northern pike at below local median levels. Bluegill and black crappie were sampled at above local median numbers. Largemouth bass and hybrid muskellunge are present. Channel catfish stocked in 1981 and sauger were sampled by electrofishing.

Bluegill were taken in low numbers. Average size and growth of BLG were above average for this area. Black bullheads were abundant, but were fair size. Black crappie were also abundant with good average size. Largemouth bass, walleye, northern pike, and sauger were taken in low numbers. Growth of northern pike was good. Growth of largemouth bass was also good. The single sauger captured is believed to be a migrant from the Mississippi - its growth was average. Four walleye were sampled - none younger than V+. The walleye sampled exhibited fast growth. One gizzard shad was sampled - probably a migrant from the Mississippi. Carp were sampled in low numbers, but small fish sampled indicate recruitment is occurring. Small numbers of yellow perch were sampled - their origin is unknown.

This back-water or river lake of the Mississippi River has a dense population of bluegills, gizzard shad, carp, and yellow perch. Fair to good numbers of crappie and largemouth bass are present. Many other game fish and rough fish find their way to the lake from the Mississippi River. The lake is small but fertile. Over wintering conditions in the lake became poor due to oxygen deficiencies.

Bluegills are the primary management species for Lake Rebecca. The trap net catch of 20.44 per set is within the normal range for this lake. The average bluegill captured was 5.96 inches and 0.15 pounds. Approximately 15% of all bluegill sampled were 7.0 inches or larger. Black crappies were sampled above median levels for abundance in the trap nets and within the median levels for the gill nets. White crappies up to 14.65 inches were also sampled. Due to the 2001 flood a number of riverine species, bowfin, carp, gizzard shad, silver redhorse, shortnose gar, and white bass are present in the lake. Walleye and sauger were sampled in low numbers. Northern pike, largemouth bass and channel catfish were sampled in good numbers.
